{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475847"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:38:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:38:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12850"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12850"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.28,0.05,0.08,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5293"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49080"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5293"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2023-05-10T13:53:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T00:05:02+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2023-05-20T10:16:23+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-01 20:04:37"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12850"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"13477"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"7568"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34114"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1919"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"6625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9078"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44140"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34114"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49080"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old boy presents with a three hour history of nose bleeding, which his parents have not been able to control. According to his mother, the boy gets easily fatigued while playing with friends his age, looks pale these days, and often feels short of breath. He has had frequent bouts of coughing and colds but has not been hospitalised for those episodes. The child and his close relatives have no overseas travel history. There is no history of drug or chemical exposure. The child consumes a non-vegetarian diet. The child has tachycardia and pallor on general examination. The liver, spleen, and lymph nodes do not appear enlarged. The rest of the systemic examination appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory evaluation shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 70 g/L (115\u2013135 g/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC of 2.10x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.00-11.00x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 50\u00d710\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (165\u2013473\u00d710\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReticulocytes 23.0 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (36.4-68.0 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aplastic anaemia","Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia","Immune thrombocytopenic purpura","Viral bone marrow suppression","Fanconi anaemia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESigns and symptoms related to the insufficiency of all cell lineages (pancytopaenia), including anaemia (progressive weakness, pallor, and dyspnoea), neutropenia (frequent and persistent minor infections), and thrombocytopenia (ecchymoses, mucosal bleeding, and petechiae), are possible in any of the provided differentials. The lack of travel history to tuberculosis-endemic areas, the absence of lymphadenopathy, splenomegaly, and hepatomegaly in a patient who consumes a non-vegetarian diet favour a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eaplastic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe best way to differentiate would be to do a peripheral blood smear and a bone marrow biopsy. The diagnostic criteria for aplastic anaemia are the presence of hypocellular bone marrow and two or more cytopaenias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute lymphoblastic leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E may present with features of pancytopaenia. However, clinical examination often reveals hepatomegaly, splenomegaly, or lymphadenopathy in the majority of cases. Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia is more common in children with Down syndrome, neurofibromatosis type 1, Bloom syndrome, and ataxia telangiectasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmune thrombocytopenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with isolated thrombocytopenia without anaemia or neutropenia. It is characterised by mucocutaneous bleeding and petechiae, but the absence of pancytopaenia makes it less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral bone marrow suppression\u003C/strong\u003E can cause transient pancytopaenia, especially following viral infections. However, the chronicity of symptoms and the absence of recent viral illness make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFanconi anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a genetic disorder that leads to bone marrow failure and pancytopaenia. It is often associated with congenital abnormalities, which are not mentioned in this case, making it a less likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pancytopaenia in the absence of splenomegaly and hepatomegaly favours a diagnosis of aplastic anaemia"],"references":["Moore CA, Krishnan K. Aplastic Anemia. [Updated 2022 Jul 18]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534212/","Chandni R, Rajan G, Udayabhaskaran V. Extra pulmonary tuberculosis presenting as fever with massive splenomegaly and pancytopenia. IDCases. 2016 Mar 2;4:20-2. doi: 10.1016/j.idcr.2016.02.005. PMID: 27051579; PMCID: PMC4802818.","Shallis RM, Ahmad R, Zeidan AM. Aplastic anemia: Etiology, molecular pathogenesis, and emerging concepts. Eur J Haematol. 2018 Dec;101(6):711-720. doi: 10.1111/ejh.13153. Epub 2018 Oct 10. PMID: 30055055.","Killick SB, Bown N, Cavenagh J, et al. Guidelines for the diagnosis and management of adult aplastic anaemia. Br J Haematol 2016; 172:187.","Torres HA, Bodey GP, Rolston KV, et al. Infections in patients with aplastic anemia: experience at a tertiary care cancer center. Cancer 2003; 98:86."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34114"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12850"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34114"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-23T15:48:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-23T15:48:30+09:30","number":4,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5293"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49080"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"2789"}},"generation":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisionGenerations","i